@R.J. Smith

Always surprised at the number of people who boast of not knowing about something no matter if it's opera, rap, sports, foreign phrases, or anything else.

We all have our own areas of interest.  No need to try to justify our blindspots.

@R.J. Smith

I loathe olives but I can't imagine saying, thank God I'm not a person who loves olives. Or some such. Strange boast.  But to each their own. 

Sorry you found it tedious. It was a delight to me. 🖖

@Francis @Steve L

Totally agree with you both!!

Also, one of the reasons I love Star Trek is it's much more ideal vision of the future. Star Wars always feels dark to me, not that I don't enjoy it to a lesser degree, but Star Trek has always given me more hope. My very favorite is TNG. Tapestry and inner light are two of my very favorite episodes. But there are so very many others.

@HeathieJ

Star Wars doesn't take place in the future.

"A long time ago in a galaxy far, far away...."

@MC. If you grew up in the Bay Area and listened to Terry McGovern on KSAN in the mornings, he did a song called “Beam Me Up Scottie”… <a href="https://youtu.be/p_bGCK4vxHA?si=gbNmJ1tDmZocT7Yd" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/p_bGCK4vxHA?si=gbNmJ1tDmZocT7Yd</a>

Hard to explain or describe now how uncool Star Trek was on the early 1970s… I think William Shatner was homeless for a while and lived in his pickup truck.  

In Berkeley there was a store called Federation Outpost that had a full set of blueprints for the Enterprise for sale… first time I found some like minded fans.  I came real close to buying a federation uniform but ended up buying a red velour jumpsuit that had wide bell bottoms, and platform shoes instead, a few doors up the street on Telegraph Ave, for the disco.  Wish I had a photo.

